const locale = getLocaleFromPath(Astro.url.pathname);
const L = (href: string) => localizeNavHref(href, locale);

const url = new URL(Astro.url.pathname, Astro.site).href;
const schemaImageUrl = new URL('/og/equipement.png', Astro.site).href;
const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'Monocrystalline or polycrystalline? String or micro-inverters?',
  description: 'Efficiency, heat behaviour, shading: how to choose between monocrystalline and polycrystalline panels, and between string inverters and micro-inverters.',
  image: schemaImageUrl,
  about: { '@type': 'Thing', name: 'Photovoltaic panels and solar inverters' },
  author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: NAP.name, url: NAP.url },
  publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: NAP.name, url: NAP.url },
  mainEntityOfPage: url,
};
---

<Layout
  title="Monocrystalline or polycrystalline? String or micro-inverters? | Taqinor"
  description="~19–22 % efficiency for mono, very different shading behaviour depending on the inverter: this guide explains how to choose your panels and inverter based on your roof, with no jargon."
  ogSlug="guides"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(jsonLd)} />
  <div class="v2">
    <V2Enhance />
    <Article33Ribbon />

    <Breadcrumb items={[{ label: 'Home', href: L('/') }, { label: 'Guides', href: L('/guides') }, { label: 'Monocrystalline or polycrystalline?' }]} />

    <article class="mx-auto max-w-[68ch] px-4 pb-24 pt-12 sm:pb-28">
      <p class="tech-label v2-kicker rule-brass text-lune">Guide · Equipment</p>
      <h1 class="display v2-page-title mt-5 text-white">Monocrystalline or polycrystalline? String or micro-inverters?</h1>

      <p class="v2-lead mt-6 text-lune-soft">
        These two questions come up as soon as you compare quotes, but for most Moroccan homes one
        of them is already settled. Here's how much each one actually deserves to keep you up at
        night, and why.
      </p>

      <h2 class="display v2-section-title mt-12 text-white">The panel: a question that's basically settled</h2>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        Honestly, the mono-versus-poly choice shouldn't take up much of your time. Monocrystalline
        has won. A monocrystalline panel is cut from a single silicon crystal, giving its cells a
        uniform structure and an efficiency of 19 to 22 % on current models: every square metre
        produces more than a poly panel of the same surface. On a tight or oddly shaped roof, that
        translates directly into extra kilowatt-peak without enlarging the installation.
      </p>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        It also handles heat better. All panels lose a bit of power as temperature rises — that's
        semiconductor physics — but monocrystalline resists this thermal degradation better. In
        Marrakech or Agadir in high summer, that matters during the hottest hours.
      </p>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        Polycrystalline, meanwhile, was the standard until the mid-2010s: cells made from several
        fused crystals, bluish look, efficiency of 15 to 17 % and more pronounced heat sensitivity.
        With prices having converged, it's no longer the default choice. It's still available, but
        in practice we install monocrystalline — and that's what you'll see on nearly every serious
        quote today. In short, on this point, your real decision-making work lies elsewhere.
      </p>

      <h2 class="display v2-section-title mt-12 text-white">The inverter: this one deserves your attention</h2>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        We install <strong class="text-white">string</strong> inverters, and only those: Deye and
        Huawei. String architecture wires several panels in series to form a "chain" that feeds a
        centralised inverter. It's simple, proven and cheaper to install. Its weak point is well
        known: if one panel is partially shaded — an antenna, a shared wall, a chimney — it drags
        the whole chain down, like the weak link in a rope.
      </p>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        That's precisely why your roof's shape weighs more than the budget in this choice. Some
        string inverters, including the Huawei SUN2000 range we install, integrate per-string
        optimisation that partly mitigates the effect of shading. On a clear roof, well oriented and
        without recurring shade — the most common case in Morocco — a string setup is more than
        enough and remains the most rational choice.
      </p>

      <h2 class="display v2-section-title mt-12 text-white">What about micro-inverters? What you should know</h2>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        You'll surely come across the terms "micro-inverters" and "optimisers" in your reading, and
        it's useful to know what they do — even though it's not what we install. A micro-inverter is
        a small converter mounted behind each panel: each module works independently, shading on one
        no longer affects the others. The power optimiser is a variant: also installed panel by
        panel, but connected to a central string inverter. Both allow
        fine-grained, panel-by-panel real-time production monitoring.
      </p>
      <p class="v2-lead mt-5 text-lune-soft">
        Their value is concentrated on truly difficult roofs: broken up, facing several directions,
        or subject to partial shading for a good part of the day. The trade-off is a higher cost and
        more components on the roof, so more parts liable to age. For configurations where these
        solutions are called for, it's better to turn to an installer who has made them their
        specialty. On the vast majority of Moroccan roofs, the right pairing remains high-density
        monocrystalline on a string inverter.
      </p>
      <RelatedLinks links={[
        { href: L('/guides/orientation-inclinaison-ombrage'), label: 'Orientation, tilt, shading' },
        { href: L('/équipement'), label: 'See the equipment' },
        { href: L('/guides'), label: 'All the guides' },
      ]} />
    </article>

    <CtaBand title="Clear roof or full of shading? We'll assess it and tell you which inverter holds up." href={L('/devis/mon-toit')} />

    <StickyCta />
  </div>
</Layout>
